name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link
type="local"
href="dummit-2004-abstract.xml"
addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 1.4</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Field</html:dfn> is traditionally defined as a set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> with two binary operators, addition (denoted <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[+]]></fr:tex>) and multiplication (denoted <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\cdot ]]></fr:tex>), satisfying the field axioms:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>Associativity of addition: for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y,z\in  F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x+y)+z=x+(y+z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Commutativity of addition: for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x+y=y+x]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Additive identity: there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in  F]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  F]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0+x=x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x+0=x]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Additive inverses: for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  F]]></fr:tex> there is a unique <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  F]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x+y=0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y+x=0]]></fr:tex>; in this case, we usually denote <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(-x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Associativity of multiplication: for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y,z\in  F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x\cdot  y)\cdot  z=x\cdot  (y\cdot  z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Commutativity of multiplication: for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\cdot  y=y\cdot  x]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Multiplicative identity: there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1\in  F]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  F]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1\cdot  x=x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\cdot  1=x]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Multiplicative inverses: for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  F]]></fr:tex> which is nonzero <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\neq 0]]></fr:tex> there is a unique <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  F]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\cdot  y=1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\cdot  x=1]]></fr:tex>; usually we denote <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{-1}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Distributivity of multiplication over addition: for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y,z\in  F]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\cdot (y+z)=(x\cdot  y)+(x\cdot  z)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x+y)\cdot  z=(x\cdot  z)+(x\cdot  y)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>Note that some of these are redundant.</fr:p><fr:p>Also note: fields are usually written in blackboard bold, and the generic field is either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> (since the German word for field is "<fr:em>Körper</fr:em>").</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
