title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{1,\alpha ,…,\alpha ^{n-1}\}]]></fr:tex> spans <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> as a vector space since it is the image of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{1,x,…,x^{n-1},…\}]]></fr:tex> and that spans <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> be the image of some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>. By the division algorithm,
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[b(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\leq \deg (r)<n=\deg (p)]]></fr:tex>. Observe if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> is the image of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> under the quotient map, then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[b(\alpha )=q(\alpha )\cdot 0+r(\alpha )=r(\alpha ).]]></fr:tex>
Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (r)<n]]></fr:tex>, we have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[b(\alpha )=c_{0}+c_{1}\alpha +…+c_{n-1}\alpha ^{n-1},]]></fr:tex>
which implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b(\alpha )=\beta \in \mathop {\textrm {span}}\nolimits (1,\alpha ,…,\alpha ^{n-1})]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> was arbitrary, and we showed it was a linear combination of the proposed basis, we have obtained the result.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
